 "components": {
  "instruction": "You are tasked with classifying user queries related to financial services, specifically those involving fintech or banking apps, into one of a set list of support or operational categories. The user's text will describe a problem or request regarding their account, transaction, or app usage. Your task is to carefully analyze the user’s description, detect the exact scenario, and then assign precisely one category—using only the fixed set of categories provided—reflecting the specific issue described.\n\nThe possible categories you must choose from are:\n\n- automatic_top_up\n- balance_not_updated_after_bank_transfer\n- beneficiary_not_allowed\n- cancel_transfer\n- card_payment_fee_charged\n- card_payment_not_recognised\n- declined_cash_withdrawal\n- exchange_rate\n- exchange_via_app\n- failed_transfer\n- get_disposable_virtual_card\n- get_physical_card\n- passcode_forgotten\n- pending_top_up\n- pending_transfer\n- receiving_money\n- reverted_card_payment?\n- top_up_by_cash_or_cheque\n- top_up_reverted\n- topping_up_by_card\n- transfer_fee_charged\n- transfer_into_account\n- transfer_timing\n- verify_my_identity\n- verify_source_of_funds\n\nKey instructions and domain details:\n\n- Read the user text carefully and determine exactly what the user is asking or reporting. Pay close attention to the details and terms used—users may describe similar problems in slightly different words, and your classification must reflect the nuanced difference.\n- Many categories are similar: for example, if the user refers to a transfer not arriving, pay close attention to whether they mean a transfer from an *external bank* failing to update their app balance (resulting in the label 'balance_not_updated_after_bank_transfer'), or whether a transfer *within the app* is simply still being processed ('pending_transfer').\n- For top-up related queries, if the user mentions their top-up being unsuccessful, canceled, or reversed, the most precise category is usually 'top_up_reverted', **not** 'cancel_transfer', 'failed_transfer', or otherwise.\n- Assign the **most specific and accurate label** available. Avoid choosing a general category if a more precise one applies, and do not select multiple labels. Response should be a single category, spelled exactly as shown.\n- Use context cues in the user's description:\n  - If the user talks about not receiving a top-up or a top-up being \"canceled\", label as 'top_up_reverted'.\n  - If the user is waiting for a bank transfer to credit their app balance, label as 'balance_not_updated_after_bank_transfer'.\n  - If the user is waiting for a transfer to someone else within the app and it is still processing, label as 'pending_transfer'.\n  - If a transaction was declined or a payment not recognized, pick the precise matching label (e.g., 'declined_cash_withdrawal', 'card_payment_not_recognised').\n  - For inquiries about fees, use the relevant fee category.\n  - For physical or virtual card requests, use 'get_physical_card' or 'get_disposable_virtual_card' as appropriate.\n- Do **not** invent categories, combine categories, or interpret beyond the information in the list above.\n\nYour output must always be:\n- A single line containing only the exact spelling of the assigned category.\n- No explanation, commentary, or extra text.\n\nInput format:\n- Each task presents a user 'text' or description—an unstructured message describing an issue or need.\n\nOutputs:\n- One category label, chosen from the list, on its own line.\n\nFailure to follow these instructions—such as choosing an incorrect or overly generic label—may result in misclassification. Be precise, attentive to context, and always favor the most accurate and specific label."
 },
